We find out some `evtx` files so let's find a tool to easily visualize the logs: https://github.com/omerbenamram/evtx

We can translate then all the files to a more readable json format:
```
find -name "*.evtx" | xargs -I % evtx_dump -f "../jsons/%.json" -o json %
```
After searching for `.exe` in all the jsons, we fin out some really weird `C:\\Temp\\blah.exe` call in `Microsoft-Windows-PowerShell%4Operational.evtx.json`

Let's try to automatically filter these files and export the content of all `ScriptBlockText` concatenated:
```
sudo apt-get install xmlstarlet
```

```
evtx_dump Microsoft-Windows-PowerShell%4Operational.evtx -f ../powershell.xml
csplit -z powershell.xml /^Record/ '{*}' # Split into files
ls xx* | xargs -I % sh -c "tail -n +2 % > new_%" # Remove first line

for file in $(ls new_xx* | sort -V); do
    xmlstarlet sel -t -v "//*[local-name()='Data'][@Name='ScriptBlockText']" "$file" >> reconstructed_output
done
```

And BOOM there we have the full reconstructed output of the terminal.
